The paper focuses on a robot grasping and block stacking task, which falls under the field of robotics (cs.RO). The use of neural networks for grasping and stacking also suggests computer vision (cs.CV) and machine learning (cs.LG) as likely sub-categories. The paper also discusses the failure of existing neural network models to generalize to this task, indicating a need for further research in artificial intelligence (cs.AI). Finally, the task involves real-time interaction with the environment, which suggests a potential connection to systems and control (cs.SY).
